re, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Schotland","Balmuto Castle, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Balmuto, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"circa 1307-1315–before 29 February 1364":"about 1315–before 29 February 1364","1303–1345":"1303–1345","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1315–1364":"1315–1364","before 29 February 1364":"before 29 February 1364","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1345":"1345","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","circa 1307-1315":"about 1315","1419":"1419","10 November 1334":"10 November 1334","circa 1345":"1345","1 January 1354":"1 January 1354","Lindisfarne Castle, Kirkcudbright, Southerland, Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Applegirth, Dumfrieshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Balmuto Castle, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Balmuto, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Glen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (central Scotland): habitational name from Glen in Traquair (Peebleshire). The placename is derived from Gaelic <i>gleann</i> ‘glen, valley’.","English: habitational name from a place so called in Leicestershire, so named from an Old English word <i>glean</i> ‘glen, valley’ (from Celtic <i>glinn</i>).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): presumably an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish names."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret De Glen Countess of Balmuto, Princess of Scotland, was born about 1315, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland. She married Robert De La Glenn, Earl of Balmuto on 10 November 1334, in Kirkcudbrightshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died before 29 February 1364, in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"circa 1307-1315–before 29 February 1364":"umbes 1315–enne 29. veebruari 1364","1303–1345":"1303–1345","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1315–1364":"1315–1364","before 29 February 1364":"enne 29. veebruari 1364","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1345":"1345","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","circa 1307-1315":"umbes 1315","1419":"1419","10 November 1334":"10. november 1334","circa 1345":"1345","1 January 1354":"1. jaanuar 1354","Lindisfarne Castle, Kirkcudbright, Southerland, Scotland":"Kirkcudbrightshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Applegirth, Dumfrieshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Balmuto Castle, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Balmuto, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"circa 1307-1315–before 29 February 1364":"noin 1315–ennen vuotta 29. helmikuuta 1364","1303–1345":"1303–1345","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1315–1364":"1315–1364","before 29 February 